{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048181,"nonce":"jfuvq+lu7c0XruEhrZPT+xCCQxk=","title":"Support alternative training methods (RL, evolutionary strategies)","message":"[Imported from GitHub #50] (created 2026-02-21T23:27:30Z)\n\n## Motivation\n\nFeedbax currently trains controllers via backprop through differentiable models (optimal control with continuous loss). This is powerful but not the only useful training paradigm. Supporting additional methods would make feedbax a more general control framework.\n\n## Candidate Methods\n\n- **PPO / policy gradient RL**: Train controllers via reward-driven rollouts. Doesn't require differentiable dynamics — works with MJX (discrete stepper) and other black-box simulators. Already implemented in bbooddyy's oracle pipeline and planned for migration to feedbax.\n- **Evolutionary strategies** (CMA-ES, OpenAI-ES): Population-based parameter optimization. Embarrassingly parallel, no gradient computation. Good for exploration-heavy problems or non-differentiable objectives.\n- **Hybrid**: Backprop for fine-tuning + RL/ES for exploration or when gradients are uninformative.\n\n## Design Considerations\n\n- The training interface should be pluggable: `TaskTrainer` (existing backprop), `PPOTrainer`, `ESTrainer` sharing a common protocol\n- RL training needs a step-based environment interface, not just `vector_field()` — see discrete dynamics discussion\n- Reward functions (effector-space) should compose with the existing loss system\n- All methods should support vmap-batched training for GPU parallelism\n\n## Relation to Other Work\n\n- MJXPlant (planned) provides the discrete-step dynamics that RL needs\n- bbooddyy issue #1 proposes migrating RL infrastructure (PPO, functional env, rewards) to feedbax\n- Existing `TaskTrainer` remains the primary path for differentiable plants\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}